            "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
            "body": "It's worth pointing out that your example at the global scope won't actually create a closure at all - it just tries to look up a global variable.\r\n\r\nIf I run it in a function scope (again in pure Python):\r\n\r\n```\r\ndef f():\r\n...   try:\r\n...     raise ValueError(\"I'm an error\")\r\n...   except ValueError as err:\r\n...     def print_err():\r\n...       print(err)\r\n...   return print_err\r\n... \r\n>>> f()()\r\nTraceback (most recent call last):\r\n  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\r\n  File \"<stdin>\", line 6, in print_err\r\nNameError: free variable 'err' referenced before assignment in enclosing scope\r\n```\r\n\r\nI get the same behaviour in Cython again.\r\n",
